        // The largest possible median for any class is `a_{2n-1}`.
        //
        // If we form a class of size `s1` and another of size `s2`, where `s1, s2` are odd and `s1+s2=2n`.
        //
        // The key insight for this type of problem is often that the optimal solution
        // involves taking contiguous elements from the sorted array.
        //
        // If we sort the array `a`, the elements `a_{n-1}` and `a_n` are the two elements
        // that would be the medians if we were to split the array into two halves of size `n` each.
        //
        // For example, if n=1, array is [a0, a1]. Class 1: [a0], Class 2: [a1]. Medians a0, a1. Diff |a1-a0|.
        // Here, n=1, so n-1=0, n=1. Diff |a_n - a_{n-1}| = |a_1 - a_0|.
        //
        // For n=3, array is [a0, a1, a2, a3, a4, a5].
        // One possible partition: Class 1: [a0, a1, a2], Class 2: [a3, a4, a5].
