        //
        // If we choose `a_{n-1}` as the median of Class 1, then Class 1 must have `k` elements smaller than `a_{n-1}`
        // and `k` elements larger than `a_{n-1}`.
        // The smallest `k` elements are `a_0, ..., a_{k-1}`.
        // The largest `k` elements are `a_{n}, ..., a_{n+k-1}`.
        // This is not correct.
        //
        // If `a_{n-1}` is the median of Class 1, then Class 1 must contain `a_{n-1}`.
        // And it must contain `k` elements from `a_0, ..., a_{n-2}` and `k` elements from `a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}`.
        // The size of Class 1 would be `2k+1`.
        //
        // Similarly, if `a_n` is the median of Class 2, then Class 2 must contain `a_n`.
        // And it must contain `j` elements from `a_0, ..., a_{n-1}` and `j` elements from `a_{n+1}, ..., a_{2n-1}`.
        // The size of Class 2 would be `2j+1`.
        //
        // The total number of students is `2n`.
        //
        // Consider the elements `a_0, ..., a_{n-1}` and `a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}`.
