        // Class B must contain `a_n`.
        // It must also contain `k_B` elements smaller than `a_n` and `k_B` elements larger than `a_n`.
        // We can pick `a_{k_A}, ..., a_{n-2}` and `a_{n+k_A}, ..., a_{2n-1}`.
        //
        // This construction is tricky because elements are shared.
        //
        // A simpler argument:
        // Let `m_A` be the median of Class A and `m_B` be the median of Class B.
        // Without loss of generality, assume `m_A <= m_B`.
        //
        // Class A has `k_A` elements smaller than `m_A` and `k_A` elements larger than `m_A`.
        // Class B has `k_B` elements smaller than `m_B` and `k_B` elements larger than `m_B`.
        //
        // The total number of elements smaller than `m_A` is at least `k_A`.
        // The total number of elements larger than `m_B` is at least `k_B`.
        //
        // The total number of elements in the array `a` is `2n`.
        //
        // Consider the elements `a_0, ..., a_{n-1}`. There are `n` such elements.
        // Consider the elements `a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}`. There are `n` such elements.
        //
        // The median of Class A, `m_A`, must be one of the `a_i`.
