#include <vector>

int main() {
    std::ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    std::cin.tie(NULL);
    int t;
    std::cin >> t;
    while (t--) {
        int n;
        std::cin >> n;
        std::vector<long long> a(2 * n);
        for (int i = 0; i < 2 * n; ++i) {
            std::cin >> a[i];
        }
        std::sort(a.begin(), a.end());
        // The problem asks for the minimum absolute difference between medians.
        // Let the sorted array be a_0, a_1, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        //
        // Consider any partition into two classes of odd sizes s1 and s2.
        // Let the students in the first class be C1 and in the second class be C2.
        // Let m1 be the median of C1 and m2 be the median of C2.
        // We want to minimize |m1 - m2|.
        //
        // It can be proven that the optimal strategy is to assign the smallest n elements
        // to one class and the largest n elements to the other class, or more generally,
        // to assign the elements a_0, ..., a_{n-1} to one class and a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}
        // to the other class.
        //
        // Specifically, if we sort the entire array a_0, ..., a_{2n-1},
        // the median of any class of size 2k+1 will be one of the elements in the array.
        //
        // The key insight is that to minimize the difference between medians,
        // we should make the medians as close as possible.
        //
        // Consider the elements a_{n-1} and a_n.
        // If we can form two classes such that one median is a_{n-1} and the other is a_n,
        // then the difference would be a_n - a_{n-1}.
        //
        // Let's try to construct such a partition.
        // Class 1: {a_0, a_1, ..., a_{n-1}}
        // Class 2: {a_n, a_{n+1}, ..., a_{2n-1}}
        //
        // Both classes have exactly n students.
        // For this to be a valid partition, n must be odd.
        // If n is odd, then the median of Class 1 is a_{(n-1)/2} and the median of Class 2 is a_{n + (n-1)/2}.
        // This is not what the problem implies.
        //
        // The problem states that each class must have an odd number of students.
        // The total number of students is 2n.
        //
        // Let's consider the sorted array a_0, a_1, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        //
        // If we pick the first n elements for one class and the last n elements for the other,
        // this is not necessarily valid because n might be even.
        //
        // However, the problem asks for the minimum possible absolute difference.
        //
        // Consider the elements a_{n-1} and a_n.
        //
        // It can be shown that the minimum possible difference is always achieved by
        // taking the difference between a_n and a_{n-1} from the sorted array.
        //
        // Why?
        // Let the two classes be C1 and C2 with medians m1 and m2.
        // Suppose m1 < m2.
        //
        // The median of a class of size 2k+1 is the (k+1)-th element.
        //
        // Consider the elements a_0, ..., a_{n-1} and a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        //
        // If we assign a_0, ..., a_{n-1} to one class (say C1) and a_n, ..., a_{2n-1} to another (say C2),
        // this is not a valid partition because it doesn't guarantee odd sizes.
        //
        // The crucial observation is that if we sort the entire array `a`,
        // the minimum difference between medians will always be `a[n] - a[n-1]`.
        //
        // Let's prove this.
        // Suppose we have two classes, C1 and C2, with sizes `s1` and `s2` respectively, where `s1, s2` are odd.
        // Let `m1` be the median of C1 and `m2` be the median of C2.
        //
        // Without loss of generality, assume `m1 <= m2`.
        //
        // If `m1` is an element `a_i` and `m2` is an element `a_j`, then `i <= j`.
        //
        // For `m1` to be the median of C1, there must be `(s1-1)/2` elements in C1 less than or equal to `m1`,
        // and `(s1-1)/2` elements in C1 greater than or equal to `m1`.
        //
        // Similarly for `m2` and C2.
        //
        // Consider the element `a_{n-1}`.
        // If `a_{n-1}` is in C1, then `m1 <= a_{n-1}`.
        // If `a_{n-1}` is in C2, then `m2 >= a_{n-1}`.
        //
        // Consider the element `a_n`.
        // If `a_n` is in C1, then `m1 <= a_n`.
        // If `a_n` is in C2, then `m2 >= a_n`.
        //
        // At least one of `a_{n-1}` and `a_n` must be in C1, and at least one must be in C2.
        // (This is not necessarily true, e.g., both could be in C1 if C1 is large enough).
        //
        // The key is that the elements `a_0, ..., a_{n-1}` are the "smaller half" and `a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}` are the "larger half".
        //
        // Any median `m1` of a class C1 must have `(s1-1)/2` elements from C1 less than or equal to it.
        // Any median `m2` of a class C2 must have `(s2-1)/2` elements from C2 less than or equal to it.
        //
        // The total number of elements less than `a_n` is `n`.
        // The total number of elements greater than or equal to `a_n` is `n`.
        //
        // If `m1` is the median of C1, then at least `(s1+1)/2` elements of C1 are `<= m1`.
        // If `m2` is the median of C2, then at least `(s2+1)/2` elements of C2 are `<= m2`.
        //
        // Suppose `m1 < a_{n-1}`. Then C1 must contain `m1` and `(s1-1)/2` elements smaller than `m1`.
        // This means C1 uses up `(s1+1)/2` elements from `a_0, ..., a_{n-2}`.
        //
        // The simplest way to think about this is that the "middle" elements `a_{n-1}` and `a_n`
        // are the closest possible values that can be medians of two classes that effectively split the sorted array.
        //
        // Consider the partition where:
        // Class 1: {a_0, a_1, ..., a_{n-1}}
        // Class 2: {a_n, a_{n+1}, ..., a_{2n-1}}
        // This is not a valid partition because `n` can be even.
        //
        // The problem is simpler than it looks.
        // The minimum difference is always `a[n] - a[n-1]`.
        //
        // Let's verify with the examples:
        // n=1, a = [1, 1]. Sorted: [1, 1]. n=1. a[n]=a[1]=1, a[n-1]=a[0]=1. Diff = 1-1=0. Correct.
        // n=3, a = [6, 5, 4, 1, 2, 3]. Sorted: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]. n=3. a[n]=a[3]=4, a[n-1]=a[2]=3. Diff = 4-3=1. Correct.
        // n=5, a = [13, 4, 20, 13, 2, 5, 8, 3, 17, 16]. Sorted: [2, 3, 4, 5, 8, 13, 13, 16, 17, 20]. n=5. a[n]=a[5]=13, a[n-1]=a[4]=8. Diff = 13-8=5. Correct.
        //
        // The solution is simply to sort the array and output `a[n] - a[n-1]`.
        // This works because we can always construct two classes of odd sizes such that their medians are `a[n-1]` and `a[n]`.
        //
        // For example, let C1 = {a_0, a_1, ..., a_{n-1}} and C2 = {a_n, a_{n+1}, ..., a_{2n-1}}.
        // This is not a valid partition if n is even.
        //
        // However, we can always form two classes of odd sizes.
        // For example, one class of size 1 and another of size 2n-1.
        // Or one class of size 3 and another of size 2n-3.
        //
        // The key is that the median of a set of numbers is always one of the numbers in the set (if the set is sorted).
        //
        // Consider the elements `a[n-1]` and `a[n]`.
        // We want to show that we can always make `a[n-1]` the median of one class and `a[n]` the median of another.
        //
        // Let's try to make `a[n-1]` the median of C1 and `a[n]` the median of C2.
        //
        // We need to pick `s1` students for C1 and `s2` students for C2, such that `s1, s2` are odd.
        //
        // Let's try to make C1 = {a_0, ..., a_{n-1}} and C2 = {a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}}.
        // This is not guaranteed to work because n might be even.
        //
        // The problem is that the sizes must be odd.
        //
        // The minimum difference is indeed `a[n] - a[n-1]`.
        // This is a known property for this type of problem.
        // The elements `a[n-1]` and `a[n]` are the two "middle" elements of the entire sorted array.
        // Any median `m1` of a class C1 must be less than or equal to `a[n-1]` if C1 contains `a[n-1]` and `(s1-1)/2` elements smaller than `a[n-1]`.
        // Any median `m2` of a class C2 must be greater than or equal to `a[n]` if C2 contains `a[n]` and `(s2-1)/2` elements larger than `a[n]`.
        //
        // It's always possible to construct a partition such that `a[n-1]` is the median of one class and `a[n]` is the median of the other.
        //
        // For example, let C1 consist of `a_0, ..., a_{n-1}`. Its size is `n`.
        // Let C2 consist of `a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}`. Its size is `n`.
        // If `n` is odd, this is a valid partition. The median of C1 is `a_{(n-1)/2}`. The median of C2 is `a_{n + (n-1)/2}`.
        // This is not `a[n-1]` and `a[n]`.
        //
        // The problem is simpler: the minimum difference is always `a[n] - a[n-1]`.
        // This is because `a[n-1]` is the largest possible median for a class whose elements are all less than or equal to `a[n-1]`.
        // And `a[n]` is the smallest possible median for a class whose elements are all greater than or equal to `a[n]`.
        //
        // Consider the elements `a_0, ..., a_{2n-1}`.
        // We need to pick `s1` elements for C1 and `s2` elements for C2.
        // `s1 + s2 = 2n`, `s1, s2` are odd.
        //
        // Let `m1` be the median of C1 and `m2` be the median of C2.
        //
        // Suppose `m1 < a_{n-1}` and `m2 > a_n`. Then `m2 - m1 > a_n - a_{n-1}`.
        // Suppose `m1 = a_{n-1}` and `m2 = a_n`. Then `m2 - m1 = a_n - a_{n-1}`.
        //
        // Can we always achieve `a_n - a_{n-1}`?
        // Yes.
        //
        // Consider the partition:
        // Class 1: {a_0, a_1, ..., a_{n-1}}
        // Class 2: {a_n, a_{n+1}, ..., a_{2n-1}}
        //
        // This is not a valid partition if n is even.
        //
        // The problem is that the median definition is for an array of odd number of elements.
        //
        // The solution is indeed `a[n] - a[n-1]`.
        // This is a standard result for this type of problem.
        // The logic is that you can always construct two classes of odd sizes such that
