            //         Here, S = 2 (even). (abs_n + abs_m) = 4 (even). S % 2 == (abs_n + abs_m) % 2. This is consistent.
            //         But k = 3 (odd). So (abs_n + abs_m) % 2 != k % 2.
            //         
            //         The parity condition is (final_x + final_y) % 2 == (number of straight moves) % 2.
            //         It is NOT (final_x + final_y) % 2 == k % 2.
            //         
            //         Let D be diagonal moves, S be straight moves. D+S=k.
            //         We want to maximize D, so minimize S.
            //         S must satisfy S % 2 == (abs_n + abs_m) % 2.
            //         Also, S >= abs_n - abs_m.
            //         
            //         So, the minimum S is:
            //         If (abs_n - abs_m) % 2 == (abs_n + abs_m) % 2:
            //           S_min = abs_n - abs_m.
            //         Else:
            //           S_min = abs_n - abs_m + 1. (This is wrong, it should be +2 to maintain parity)
            //           No, it should be abs_n - abs_m + 1 if we can convert one diagonal to one straight.
            //           
            //           Let's use the property that (x,y) parity changes.
