            }

            current_val = (current_val << 1) | (s[j] - '0');

            if (current_val == len) {
                good_substrings_count++;
            }
        }

        // Case 2: Substrings starting with '1'
        // If s[i] is '1', then f(s[i...r]) = 2^(r-i) + f(s[i+1...r]).
        // The length is r - i + 1.
        // We need r - i + 1 = f(s[i...r]).
        // As discussed, if s[i] is '1', then f(s[i...r]) >= 2^(r-i).
        // If r-i >= 19, then 2^(r-i) >= 2^19 = 524288, which is greater than N (2e5).
        // So, we only need to check for r-i up to 18.
        // This means r can be at most i + 18.
        // This is already covered by the loop above with `len <= 25`.
        // The loop `for (int j = i; j < n; ++j)` calculates `current_val` for `s[i...j]`.
        // `len = j - i + 1`.
        // If `s[i]` is '1', `current_val` will grow quickly.
        // If `current_val` exceeds `n + MAX_BITS_FOR_N`, we can stop.
        // `n + MAX_BITS_FOR_N` is roughly `2e5 + 20`.
        // `current_val` can be at most `2^60` if it's `long long`.
        // But we only care if `current_val == len`.
        // If `current_val > n + 20` (a loose upper bound for `len`), we can break.
        // The `len > 25` check already handles this.
    }

    std::cout << good_substrings_count << std::endl;
}

