#include <algorithm>
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

int main() {
    std::ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    std::cin.tie(NULL);
    int t;
    std::cin >> t;
    while (t--) {
        int n;
        std::cin >> n;
        std::vector<long long> a(2 * n);
        for (int i = 0; i < 2 * n; ++i) {
            std::cin >> a[i];
        }
        std::sort(a.begin(), a.end());
        // The problem asks to partition 2n students into two classes,
        // each with an odd number of students.
        // Let the sizes of the two classes be S1 and S2.
        // S1 + S2 = 2n. S1 and S2 must both be odd.
        // The smallest possible odd size is 1.
        // The largest possible odd size is 2n-1.
        //
        // Consider the sorted array of all 2n skill levels: a_0, a_1, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        //
        // Let's say Class 1 has size S1 = 2k1 + 1. Its median is the (k1+1)-th element.
        // Let's say Class 2 has size S2 = 2k2 + 1. Its median is the (k2+1)-th element.
        //
        // The key insight is that to minimize the difference between medians,
        // we should try to make the medians as close as possible.
        //
        // If we sort all 2n skill levels, the median of a class of size 2k+1
        // will be some element from the sorted list.
        //
        // Consider the specific partition where Class 1 takes the first n elements
        // and Class 2 takes the last n elements.
        // This is not allowed because n might be even, making the class size even.
        //
        // However, if we consider the sorted array a_0, ..., a_{2n-1},
        // the median of any class of size 2k+1 must be one of these values.
        //
        // The problem statement implies that we can choose any odd sizes for the classes.
        // The simplest odd sizes are 1 and 2n-1.
        // If Class 1 has size 1, its median is its single element.
        // If Class 2 has size 2n-1, its median is the n-th element (index n-1) if sorted.
        //
        // The crucial observation is that the minimum difference is achieved
        // when the two medians are a[n-1] and a[n].
        //
        // To see why:
        // Suppose we have two classes, C1 and C2, with odd sizes.
        // Let m1 be the median of C1 and m2 be the median of C2.
        //
        // If we sort all 2n students, a_0, a_1, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        //
        // Consider the partition where Class 1 consists of students with skills
        // a_0, a_1, ..., a_{n-1}. This class has n students.
        // Class 2 consists of students with skills a_n, a_{n+1}, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        // This class also has n students.
        //
        // If n is odd, then both classes have odd sizes.
        // The median of Class 1 would be a_{(n-1)/2}.
        // The median of Class 2 would be a_{n + (n-1)/2}.
        //
        // If n is even, this partition is invalid.
        //
        // The problem is simpler than it seems.
        // The minimum difference is always between a[n-1] and a[n].
        //
        // We can always construct a valid partition to achieve this.
        // Let the two medians be a[n-1] and a[n].
        //
        // Class 1: {a[n-1]} (size 1, median a[n-1])
        // Class 2: {all other 2n-1 students} (size 2n-1)
        // The median of Class 2 (if sorted) would be the ( (2n-1-1)/2 + 1 )-th element,
        // which is the n-th element.
        // If we put a[n-1] into Class 1, then Class 2 contains all elements except a[n-1].
        // The elements in Class 2 are a_0, ..., a_{n-2}, a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        // If we sort these 2n-1 elements, the n-th element (index n-1) would be a_n.
        // So, this partition gives medians a[n-1] and a[n].
        //
        // This is a valid partition:
        // Class 1: {a[n-1]} (size 1, median a[n-1])
        // Class 2: {a[0], ..., a[n-2], a[n], ..., a[2n-1]} (size 2n-1, median a[n])
        //
        // The absolute difference is |a[n] - a[n-1]|.
        //
        // Can we do better?
        // Suppose we have two classes C1 and C2 with medians m1 and m2.
        // Let m1 < m2.
        //
        // If m1 is the median of C1 (size 2k1+1), then C1 must contain at least k1+1 elements <= m1.
        // If m2 is the median of C2 (size 2k2+1), then C2 must contain at least k2+1 elements >= m2.
        //
        // The total number of elements less than or equal to m1 is at least k1+1.
        // The total number of elements greater than or equal to m2 is at least k2+1.
        //
        // The total number of elements is 2n.
        //
        // Consider the elements a_0, ..., a_{n-1} and a_n, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        //
        // Any median of a class must be one of the a_i values.
        //
        // The minimum possible difference between any two elements in the sorted array
        // is between adjacent elements.
        //
        // The problem is essentially asking for the minimum difference between
        // the (k1+1)-th element of one odd-sized subset and the (k2+1)-th element
        // of another odd-sized subset, where the subsets form a partition.
        //
        // The crucial part is that the median of a class of size $2k+1$ is the $(k+1)$-th element.
        //
        // If we take the $n$-th element (index $n-1$) and the $(n+1)$-th element (index $n$)
        // from the fully sorted array, these are $a[n-1]$ and $a[n]$.
        //
        // We can form Class 1 with $a[n-1]$ as its median.
        // We can form Class 2 with $a[n]$ as its median.
        //
        // The simplest way to achieve this is to put $a[n-1]$ into Class 1 (size 1).
        // And put all other $2n-1$ students into Class 2.
        // The median of Class 2 (which has $2n-1$ students) will be the $n$-th student
        // in its sorted list.
        // The students in Class 2 are $a_0, \dots, a_{n-2}, a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // When sorted, the $n$-th student (0-indexed $n-1$) in this list is $a_n$.
        // So the medians are $a[n-1]$ and $a[n]$.
        // The difference is $a[n] - a[n-1]$.
        //
        // This is the minimum possible difference because any two medians $m_1, m_2$
        // must be chosen from the $2n$ skill levels.
        // If $m_1 < m_2$, then $m_1$ must be $a_i$ and $m_2$ must be $a_j$ for some $i < j$.
        // The smallest possible difference $a_j - a_i$ for $i < j$ is $a_{i+1} - a_i$.
        //
        // The specific construction above shows that $a[n] - a[n-1]$ is achievable.
        //
        // The problem is a bit of a trick. The constraints on odd class sizes and medians
        // seem to suggest a complex partitioning, but the optimal solution is always
        // to pick the two middle elements of the fully sorted array as the medians.
        //
        // Example 1: n=1, a = [1, 1]. Sorted: [1, 1].
        // n-1 = 0, n = 1. a[0]=1, a[1]=1. Diff = |1-1|=0. Correct.
        //
        // Example 2: n=3, a = [6, 5, 4, 1, 2, 3]. Sorted: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6].
        // n-1 = 2, n = 3. a[2]=3, a[3]=4. Diff = |4-3|=1. Correct.
        //
        // Example 3: n=5, a = [13, 4, 20, 13, 2, 5, 8, 3, 17, 16].
        // Sorted: [2, 3, 4, 5, 8, 13, 13, 16, 17, 20].
        // n-1 = 4, n = 5. a[4]=8, a[5]=13. Diff = |13-8|=5. Correct.

        std::cout << a[n] - a[n - 1] << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}

